<main style='min-height:100vh;padding-bottom:20px'><header style='max-width:900px;margin:0 auto;padding:60px 20px 34px;text-align:center'><h1 style='color:#f0ece4;font-size:2.5rem;margin:0 0 14px'>Lesson Library</h1><p style='color:#b8b2a6;font-size:1.08rem;line-height:1.65;max-width:660px;margin:0 auto'>Three free courses, written for The Mind’s Gambit. Pick your level and take the lessons in order — each one teaches a single idea, then sends you to the right training tool to practice it. No account, no signup.</p></header><section style='max-width:1000px;margin:0 auto;padding:8px 20px 34px'><div style='display:flex;align-items:center;gap:14px'><span style='font-size:2.1rem;color:#d4af37'>♟</span><div><span style='display:inline-block;background:#7dd87d22;color:#7dd87d;border:1px solid #7dd87d55;border-radius:999px;padding:3px 14px;font-size:.74rem;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:700'>Beginner</span><h2 style='margin:6px 0 0;color:#f0ece4;font-size:1.5rem'>First Steps</h2></div></div><p style='color:#b8b2a6;margin:12px 0 20px;line-height:1.6'>Never played a game in your life? Perfect. Start at Lesson 1 and do not skip ahead — each lesson stands on the one before it.</p><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>1</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>The Board and the Pieces</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Chess is played on a board of 64 squares by two armies of 16 pieces. That is all the equipment you will ever need — the rest happens in your mind.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Set the board so each player has a light square in the bottom-right corner. Queens start on their own color: the white queen on a light square, the black queen on a dark one.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Each piece moves in its own way. Rooks travel in straight lines. Bishops glide along diagonals. The queen does both. Knights jump in an L-shape — the only piece allowed to leap over others. Pawns walk one square forward but capture diagonally. The king steps one square in any direction.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>A rough guide to value: a pawn is worth 1, knights and bishops about 3, a rook 5, the queen 9. The king has no number — lose him and you lose the game.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Open the lesson below and move every piece until each one feels natural.</p><a href='/chess-school/learn-to-play' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Learn to Play &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>2</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>Check, Checkmate and Stalemate</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>The whole game has one goal: trap the enemy king.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>When a king is attacked, that is <strong style='color:#f0ece4'>check</strong>. The rules demand you deal with it at once — move the king, block the attack, or capture the attacker.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>When a king is attacked and there is no escape at all, that is <strong style='color:#f0ece4'>checkmate</strong>. The game ends on the spot, no matter how many pieces are left on the board.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'><strong style='color:#f0ece4'>Stalemate</strong> is the strange cousin: the king is NOT in check, but the player to move has no legal move anywhere. That is a draw — half a point each. Many a winning game has been thrown away by a careless stalemate, and many a lost one saved by a clever one.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Play a few games against our friendliest engine level and watch for all three.</p><a href='/chess-school/play' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Play the Engine &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>3</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>The Three Golden Rules of the Opening</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>The first ten moves of a chess game can feel like a mystery. They are not. Three rules cover almost everything.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'><strong style='color:#f0ece4'>One: fight for the center.</strong> The four central squares are the high ground of the board — pieces placed there reach everywhere. Push a center pawn and aim your pieces at the middle.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'><strong style='color:#f0ece4'>Two: develop your pieces.</strong> Knights and bishops do nothing on the back row. Each early move should bring a new piece into the game. Try not to move the same piece twice, and keep the queen home a little while — she is too valuable to be chased around.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'><strong style='color:#f0ece4'>Three: castle early.</strong> Castling tucks your king behind a wall of pawns and wakes up a rook in a single move. It is the best move in chess that beginners forget to play.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Start a game and follow the three rules. You will reach a healthy position every time.</p><a href='/chess-school/play' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Play a Game &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>4</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>How to Win Material</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Most games between new players are not decided by brilliance. They are decided by free pieces — given away and gratefully taken.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>So before every single move, ask two questions. First: <em>what is my opponent threatening?</em> Second: <em>what can I take — and is it really free?</em></p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>To know if something is really free, count. How many of my pieces attack that square? How many of theirs defend it? If attackers outnumber defenders, the capture usually works. If not, the piece that looks free may bite back.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>This habit — threat first, capture second — will win you more games than any opening trick ever written.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Sharpen the habit on our puzzles: every position has something to find.</p><a href='/chess-school/puzzles' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Daily Puzzle &rarr;</a></div></details></section><section style='max-width:1000px;margin:0 auto;padding:8px 20px 34px'><div style='display:flex;align-items:center;gap:14px'><span style='font-size:2.1rem;color:#d4af37'>♞</span><div><span style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af3722;color:#d4af37;border:1px solid #d4af3755;border-radius:999px;padding:3px 14px;font-size:.74rem;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:700'>Intermediate</span><h2 style='margin:6px 0 0;color:#f0ece4;font-size:1.5rem'>Building Strength</h2></div></div><p style='color:#b8b2a6;margin:12px 0 20px;line-height:1.6'>You know the rules and you have played real games. Now we sharpen the sword: tactics, endgames, and learning from the great players.</p><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>1</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>Forks, Pins and Skewers</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Almost every game between improving players is decided by tactics — short, forcing sequences that win material or deliver mate. Three patterns appear again and again.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>The <strong style='color:#f0ece4'>fork</strong>: one piece attacks two targets at once. Knights are famous for it — a knight hop that hits king and queen together ends arguments quickly.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>The <strong style='color:#f0ece4'>pin</strong>: a piece cannot move, because something more valuable stands behind it on the same line. A pinned defender is barely a defender at all.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>The <strong style='color:#f0ece4'>skewer</strong>: the pin reversed. The valuable piece stands in front, is forced to move, and what hid behind it falls.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Nobody sees tactics by talent. We see them by pattern recognition, and patterns are built one way: repetition. Solve a handful every day and the board starts whispering to you.</p><a href='/chess-school/tactics' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Tactics Trainer &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>2</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>Endgame Essentials</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>When most pieces have left the board, the game changes character — and so does your king. He stops being someone you protect and becomes a fighting piece. March him toward the center.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Learn the two basic checkmates — king and queen, then king and rook — until you can play them with your eyes closed. Drive the enemy king to the edge, square by square, and never let him slip back.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Then learn the single most important endgame idea: <strong style='color:#f0ece4'>the opposition</strong>. Two kings face each other with one square between them — and the player who does NOT have to move usually wins the standoff.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Finally, respect the passed pawn — a pawn with no enemy pawn left to stop it. In the endgame it is not a small thing inching forward. It is a future queen.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Train these until they are reflexes.</p><a href='/chess-school/tactics?theme=endgame' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Endgame Trainer &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>3</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>Learn from the Masters</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Every strong player you will ever meet did the same thing: they played through the games of the great masters, slowly, and asked questions.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Here is the method. Open a famous game. Before each move by the winner, cover the next move and guess it. When you are wrong — and you will often be wrong — stop and ask three questions: <em>What was the threat? Why this piece and not another? What would I have played?</em></p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>You are not memorizing moves. You are borrowing, for an hour, the eyes of a master — and some of what they see stays with you.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>One game studied slowly is worth twenty skimmed.</p><a href='/chess-school/featured-games' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Featured Games &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>4</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>Plans, Not Just Moves</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>At some point, knowing tactics is not enough — you need to know what to do when nothing is hanging. That is called a plan, and plans grow out of the pawns.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Pawns are the skeleton of the position. They move slowly and never backward, so they tell you the long-term truth: where the open files are (give them to your rooks), where the strong squares are (park a knight there), and which bishop is proud or buried behind its own pawns.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>And when you truly have no idea what to do, use the oldest advice in chess: find your worst-placed piece and make it better. A position improves one piece at a time.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Load one of your own games into the analysis board and look for these signs — open files, outposts, good and bad bishops.</p><a href='/chess-school/analyze' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Game Analysis &rarr;</a></div></details></section><section style='max-width:1000px;margin:0 auto;padding:8px 20px 34px'><div style='display:flex;align-items:center;gap:14px'><span style='font-size:2.1rem;color:#d4af37'>♛</span><div><span style='display:inline-block;background:#d97b7b22;color:#d97b7b;border:1px solid #d97b7b55;border-radius:999px;padding:3px 14px;font-size:.74rem;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:700'>Advanced</span><h2 style='margin:6px 0 0;color:#f0ece4;font-size:1.5rem'>Toward Mastery</h2></div></div><p style='color:#b8b2a6;margin:12px 0 20px;line-height:1.6'>Strong club play begins here: disciplined calculation, honest analysis of your own games, and deep study of the classics.</p><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>1</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>Calculate Like a Master</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Strong players do not calculate everything. They calculate the right things, in the right order.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Begin every critical position by listing <strong style='color:#f0ece4'>candidate moves</strong> — and list the forcing moves first: checks, captures, threats. Forcing moves narrow the future; quiet moves multiply it.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Take one candidate at a time and follow it to a quiet position — do not jump between lines, that is how variations get tangled. Judge the final position honestly: better, equal, or worse?</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>And before your hand touches the piece, perform the blunder-check: <em>after my move, what is every check, capture and threat my opponent has?</em> One disciplined second of this saves a hundred lost games.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>The Position Explorer is your sparring partner: set up any position, calculate first by yourself, then let the engine argue with you.</p><a href='/chess-school/position-explorer' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Position Explorer &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>2</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>Analyze Your Own Games</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Your own games are the best chess teacher you will ever have — they show you, with total honesty, what you actually do under pressure.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>The method matters. First, replay the game WITHOUT an engine and write down what you thought at the key moments. Find the single moment where the game turned — there nearly always is one.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Only then turn the engine on. Where its judgment disagrees with yours, stop. That gap between what you believed and what was true — that exact gap — is your chess. Close it one game at a time.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Do this for every serious game you play, win or lose. Especially the wins: they hide their lessons better.</p><a href='/chess-school/position-explorer' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Analyze a Game &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>3</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>Study the Classics</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Modern games are sharp and concrete, but the old masters teach with a clarity nobody has matched since — one idea at a time, carried out to the end.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Study Morphy and you learn development and attack — chess as clean logic. Study Capablanca and you learn the endgame and simplicity — chess as flowing water. Study Tal and you learn courage — chess as fire. Each great player is a complete course with a personality.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Always study whole games, opening to endgame, not fragments. Openings show fashion; endings show truth.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Our games library is built for exactly this kind of slow reading.</p><a href='/chess-school/games' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Games Library &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:12px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:16px 20px'><span style='min-width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700'>4</span><span style='flex:1;color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;font-size:1.05rem'>Build a Study Routine</span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open lesson</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 22px 22px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Improvement at chess is not a sprint, and it is not a mystery. It is a routine kept honestly.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>A simple weekly mix that works: tactics every day, even just fifteen minutes — this is non-negotiable. One master game studied slowly. One endgame idea drilled until automatic. And real games — played with full attention, then analyzed the way Lesson 2 taught you.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>Notice what the routine does not include: hours of memorizing opening lines. At club level, openings decide far fewer games than tactics and endgames do. Spend your hours where the points are.</p><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 13px'>When you want more — books, films, further study — our resources page is the door.</p><a href='/chess-school/resources' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:4px'>Practice: Chess Resources &rarr;</a></div></details></section><section style="max-width:1000px;margin:0 auto;padding:0 20px 14px"><div style="border:1px solid rgba(212,175,55,.35);border-radius:12px;padding:16px 20px;display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start"><span style="font-size:1.4rem">📖</span><p style="color:#c9c3b6;margin:0;line-height:1.6;font-size:.95rem"><strong style="color:#f0ece4">Go deeper with the course in book form:</strong> <em>Build Up Your Chess 1: The Fundamentals</em> by Artur Yusupov — the first volume of the most respected training series ever written. Finish our courses, then start his. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/1906552010?tag=mybstudio20-20" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored" style="color:#d4af37;font-weight:700">View on Amazon →</a><br/><span style="color:#8a8478;font-size:.8rem">As an Amazon Associate, The Mind’s Gambit earns from qualifying purchases.</span></p></div></section>
<section style='max-width:1000px;margin:0 auto;padding:6px 20px 70px'><div style='background:linear-gradient(135deg,rgba(212,175,55,.13),rgba(212,175,55,.04));border:1px solid rgba(212,175,55,.35);border-radius:16px;padding:30px;text-align:center'><h2 style='color:#d4af37;margin:0 0 10px;font-size:1.45rem'>Want a guide on the journey?</h2><p style='color:#b8b2a6;margin:0 auto 18px;max-width:560px;line-height:1.6'>Lessons teach ideas — a coach teaches <em>you</em>. Learn live, one on one, in our online classroom with a professional coach.</p><a href='/chess-school/grandmasters/maryana-huda' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:12px 26px;border-radius:10px;text-decoration:none;margin:4px'>Meet Our Coach</a><a href='/#contact' style='display:inline-block;border:1px solid #d4af37;color:#d4af37;font-weight:700;padding:12px 26px;border-radius:10px;text-decoration:none;margin:4px'>Request a Lesson</a></div></section></main>
